Bakal's tenant: The boilers are heating up, he signed a higher rent.
An imposing old man walked out the door of the Byty RPG company's customer centre to "coal baron" Zdenek Bakal, the largest private owner of apartments for rent in the Czech Republic.
He was carrying a file with three new leases for three apartments: his own, his daughter's and his son's, who is serving a sentence.
The deregulation has increased the rent for these three people.
Instead of paying 3500 the son will have to pay from next year for a 2+1 second-class apartment 4100 crowns.
"And there is no hot water and the heater runs on solid fuel", points out the man who has the signature power on his son's new contract.
"But I signed anyway", he explains in a moved and half-resigned rage.
The citizens' association of apartments BytyOKD.cz, which described the new rental conditions as "immoral and indecent", advises tenants not to sign and wait until 7 December, when a notice will be published explaining the method to apply.
But the man responds to this by a gesture of his hand.
"One says this, the other says something else" by frowning.
The Ostrava region is becoming the deregulation laboratory.
After the New Year, this is what most apartments in the Czech Republic expect, whose rent does not match the market price.
Aktualne.cz has therefore decided to visit the "laboratory" personally.
The RPG waiting room on Havirovska Street is one of four in the Ostrava region and it's already full on Tuesday at 9am.
Right next to the door is a security guard with a phone to call customers.
A special button, "2011 rent", is on the touch screen.
One press and a paper with a number comes out of the device.
You don't have time to read your number "157" because your number is already starting to shine on the big screen under the ceiling of the waiting room.
In a fraction of a second, it's your turn.
After a short while, an old couple comes to inquire about the rent, but the new rent doesn't seem to apply to the people in the waiting room.
Most people have come to solve common problems like everywhere - claims for repairs, insurance events and so on.
In the Ostrava region, people in more than 44,000 RPG apartment portfolio have been collecting mail with new leases in their mailboxes since about mid-November.
RPG Byty offers them rental increases of 15 to 38 percent.
The special ticket office for new rents has been open to the public since 18 November.
"It's been working for almost a week, so it's still in the testing stage", replies the employee behind the counter after a moment of hesitation when the client presents himself as a journalist.
The deforestation and former miners' apartments in Bakal are a very sensitive local issue.
The deputy speaker of parliament from the Ostrava region Lubomir Zaoralek of the Social Democrats reported this quite consistently before the elections and it is now in the local newspapers.
"20 years after them, I want a new floor".
"They didn't even change me a put...n board in the bathroom", relieves the man mentioned in the introduction.
However, according to the employees, it is mainly retired people who come to make sure they will receive a refund on the new rent price if they sign now as RPG promised in a special offer.
This is a refund of half the rent amount that will be received by the other tenants who have signed their new lease before December 15.
But the "de-regulation" shop on Havirovaska Street is not really overwhelmed by the questions.
"Of the 360 customers who came yesterday, only 40 to 50 came for rent", says the shopkeeper.
And yet RPG does put individual rent interviews on its website and in the showcases when necessary.
If the parties do not agree on the rent, an independent court will decide.
'This is not about threats but only about informing about the unique and legitimate way to act legally,' RPG says on its website.
"No one is going to court here", one of the employees at RPG Byty thinks, and the man in the street outside the customer center is right.
"I have 13,000 pensioners and I have 5,000 to eat, I don't have enough to go to court", he says.
The employee suddenly feels uncomfortable.
"We'll see".
"Mr Zaoralek in the media is asking that no one sign and so people are waiting", she said.
Rent regulation ends in the Czech Republic with the beginning of 2011 and the increases, according to RPG Byty, are an economic necessity.
"Moreover, current rents still do not reach the level necessary for the simple maintenance of the housing fund", recalls Pavel Klimes, director of the RPG Byty housing portfolio, who said that it was the neglect of the housing fund that angered the tenant that was the main reason for the increase in rent.
However, in 5 years between 2005 and 2010 RPG was able to invest with rent 4 billion apartments, in four years from 2011 to 2014 it is expected to be 5.2 billion.
The large screen hanging from the ceiling in front of the padded chairs in the waiting room on Havirosvka Street, however, repeats some information indicated in red.
'The increase in rent in 2011 is 15 per cent and concerns no less than 31200 apartments or more than 90 per cent of RPG apartments.'
"And it will always be at most 7.50 Czech crowns per square metre per month", says the screen.
The 38 percent increase is only for 400 apartments in the RPG portfolio.
"In these cases, this is an increase of a really very low amount of 19.66 Czech crowns per m2", adds RPG.
Next year, the rent will stay the same for 2,600 apartments.
RPG Byty promises that deregulation will not cause a radical but gradual increase over four to eight years.
It adds further commitments: all the money from the increase in rent (see graph) is given to apartments in the form of heating savings - new windows and heating.
Those who sign the rental agreement have priority.
The nursery school is also part of the offices understood by the architects.
The Avriopoint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch. Design.
No one would have expected it to also house a mini preschool with everything it needed - colorful walls, imaginative furniture, toys, and finally a miniature playground on the terrace.
Since October last year, children of Arch. design employees have been able to visit.
The architectural project firm Arch. Design, whose workshops produced a large number of buildings in Brno, has conceived its mini business nursery school since the first drafts of the Avriopoint building.
She employs about 90 people, mostly of childbearing age, and she cared that women architects and project managers could return to work quickly.
Along with reduced-time employment contracts, the preschool is a bonus offered to its employees by the company Arch. Design. as part of its social programme.
This gives builders and architects the opportunity to combine carefully designed work with care for children.
It was the employees of Arch.Design who conceived this nursery school themselves and with the support of management they were able to obtain a grant from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The mini-nursery school is financed by the European Social Fund through the operational programme on human resources and the State Budget of the Czech Republic.
The funds (in the amount of CHK 2.8 million) allowed them to buy equipment and equipment and, after two years, to provide qualified staff and start-up.
After using the funding allocation (two years), the company Arch. Design. is obliged to operate the mini preschool on its own funds after 3 years.
The preparation of the project took a year and the Economy rating company helped to apply for the grant.
Childcare is provided by qualified staff, with a nurse and a kindergarten teacher taking care of children all day long.
Since this is a "mini-nursery school", there can be only 5 children present at a time, but during the day there are more who take their place.
The school is flexible in functioning according to the needs of the parents and the children of all employees have the same right to use the school regardless of the hierarchical position.
Although it is a matter of individual care and education, the curriculum of the mini preschool is comparable to that of preschool education.
Children not only play here but also get quality education - from beginners to school prep, English is taught.
The classroom is equipped not only with imaginative toys and games but also with a computer that children can use.
The presence of young children in society creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can control their child at any time and do not have the stress of being late to pick up the children at a school far from the parents' workplace.
So parents use their working time in the most productive way possible.
It is not surprising that a natural loyalty relationship develops between the employee and the employer.
Arch.Design.s is thus listed among the companies that offer a bonus of choice for recruiting new employees and are family-friendly and through this programme strengthens HR marketing.
The bone house still fascinates after 100 years.
The roof resembles the back of a prehistoric saurian, the staircase to a dinosaur spine, and the balconies to open fish mouths.
This is the Casa Battlo in Barcelona designed by architect Antoni Gaudi.
Because of its organic shape, the house has been nicknamed the Bone House by the locals.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stones, fragments of tiles and mosaics, a façade reminiscent of scales and curves everywhere, are all that are epic about Antoni Gaudi's Art Nouveau.
The front of the house unfolds its dream lines, its pleasant colors and textures that recall nature and animals.
A more detailed observation shows the precise geometry, rhythm and order.
At night the façade of the house becomes even more dramatic and is lit in such a way that the impression of bright colors is enhanced.
The rolling and twisting of the shapes also appear in the interiors with the same measure.
The wood waves the window frames, balustrades, decorative elements of the doors, the oily and the lamellae.
The Battlo house, which stands in the Eixample district on Passeig Street in Gracia at number 43, was born from the construction of an 1877 house by the architect Emilio Sala Cortes.
The rebuilding took two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, Joseph Battlo, a wealthy contractor, first insisted on demolishing the old building and building another entirely new one but quickly accepted Gaudi's idea of an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
But the idea of Casa Battlo as a multi-unit house was not conceived by Gaudi alone.
Architect Josep Maria Jujol worked with him.
It was precisely on his project that the decorations for an apartment representing the building's owner and the use of mosaic for the facade were born.
Other artists and designers also worked on the facade.
The joint work for the plans for the Casa Battlo house began with a successful cooperation between Jujol and Gaudi.
Jujol participated in the construction of Gaudi's Casa Mila house and the Guell Park which houses other works by Gaudi.
The locals nicknamed the house after its completion "the Bone House" because of its organic shapes.
Others, considering the specific mechanism of opening the windows, called it "the house that's bailing".
They say there's a sword like St. George's at the top of the building, the patron saint of Catalonia.
Other sculptural elements of the building contain hidden religious motives.
Gaudi thought of a unique system for the house in his central heating era, with typical air vents and fireplaces.
Their 45-degree tilt seems strange.
In the course of his creation Gaudi absolutely did not follow the building directives of the time and did not let himself be hindered by them.
At the start of construction he obtained permission from the city to build, knowing, of course, that the data on the reconstruction plans were so vague that two years later during the completion the city council was horrified and asked for changes.
For example, the members of the city council did not like the fact that the building columns were encircling the public sidewalk.
There was never any change, but, on the contrary, only 15 days after the city's call Josep Battlo asked (and was satisfied) for permission to rent the two highest floors.
The owner moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a common living room and on the third a bedroom and a private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewellery store.
The entire six-story house is divided by a staircase leading to an independent roof terrace.
All straight angles and straight lines were cancelled by the basic elements of the reconstruction and replaced by curved walls.
Gaudi also worked on the modern concept of connecting spaces.
The common part can be completely connected by opening the doors of the living rooms and the high society can communicate comfortably or limit private space for more intimate conversations.
The house with Gaudi's reconstruction was given a non-traditional roof and two additional floors.
Gaudi's play with light is also impressive, with blue and white glass tiles decorating the interior courtyard and with lighting wells.
The two-color game gives maximum lighting to every floor of the house.
All we had to do was bet on the principle that white reflects more than dark, which on the contrary absorbs the sun's rays.
The Casa Battlo, which was inscribed in 2005 on the UNESCO World Heritage List, is a place that everyone can visit.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and splendid apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to take this step in 2002 on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous designer.
They continued the visits as they found that this was a lucrative business and they extended the field of visits to the common areas and the attic including roof terraces.
The entrance fee for the monument is really low and costs 16.50 euros; students, pensioners, groups and tourist card holders have 20 percent discount.
The sum is still above the entry price to other Gaudi buildings in the city.
If you want to feel the real atmosphere of the house with its fantastic towers, you must quickly find a companion among the building's inhabitants and visit the house completely.
