The demand for people tracking devices is increasing among parents who want to monitor their children.
Fear for their children is making more and more people think about monitoring them using a GPS.
The system, which was initially set up to search for cars, can also be used to track people's movements and help in some cases, such as the one of little Anicka Janatkova.
The instrument is currently as large as a box of lighters but will soon be the size of a watch.
The case of little Anicka moved many people and they began to look for ways to better protect their children.
Even if the price is to disturb their privacy.
"We are trying to tell everyone that this is not espionage but just another way to reduce the likelihood of another tragedy", says Petr Pilin of the company MAcro Weil, one of the leading suppliers of tracking devices to the Czech market.
"I admit there may be cases of misuse of such devices, such as putting them in a person's bag who is not aware of them, but I have not yet encountered such cases".
"Most people are customers who actually buy the product for safety reasons", adds Pilin.
He said children should always know what the "box" is used for and how to use it in an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bockova points out that if a child does not want to wear something like this, he will get rid of it.
'And even the smallest can show great creativity when it comes to deliberately getting rid of something when they don't want to be in control.'
"Mobile phones, which can cut off like tracking devices, have already brought parents to long-term expectations", says Bockova.
She said that the fact that this type of device could help in the event of an attack is highly questionable.
"If this is a prepared abduction, the perpetrator will do everything in his power to ensure that the child does not have an electronic device that can locate him".
"It's the phone now".
"As soon as the tracking devices are developed, they will also go after them because the sale will be supported by an advertising campaign".
"In such cases, criminals will always be ahead of the police", says the psychologist.
She admits that such devices can help with unprepared child abuse.
According to Robert Cech of RC Monitoring, which provides tracking services for both cars and people, having this type of device can help, even if it is destroyed in the event of an assault.
'The apparatus may be set to be in regular emission after a specified period.'
"In the event that the device is destroyed, the last position of the person concerned remains".
'The more expensive devices also have an inclinometer that immediately signals the position of the person who slipped and is in a straight-line position,' says Cech.
He said that so-called smart phones with a navigation system can offer a comparable service after being formatted with special prologue software.
The problem with current tracking systems is that they are either a device similar to those worn in a pendant the size of a lighting box or smaller telephone devices.
We can always lose them.
According to Pilina of Macro Weil, this is why tests are being conducted to make devices that look like common digital watches.
"It would be advantageous if the attacker could not recognize the tracking device".
"Or he will find out after a while, which will have given the police a little more time", he adds.
Whether the tracking device is developed in the form of a bracelet or a pendant, it will always use the same technology as for tracking cars.
It is a combination of GPS positioning systems (which is commonly used in self-navigation) and a mobile phone function that alerts the current position of a vehicle.
