A longer index than the ring finger is a sign of a low risk of cancer
Men with a longer index than the thumb are at lower risk of developing prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published Wednesday in the British magazine Cancer.
It may depend on the level of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our findings show that the relative length of the finger is a simple test for prostate cancer risk, especially for men under 60", said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help determine which men should be tested for prostate cancer, including by combining it with genetic risk or other aggravating factors such as family health history, Eeles added.
During the period 1994-2009, she and her colleagues in Britain followed over 1500 patients with prostate cancer and at the same time nearly 3,000 healthy men.
More than half of the participants in the study had a shorter right hand index finger than the thumb index.
For them, as for the 19 percent of those who had the same length of fingers, the same probability of prostate cancer was found.
However, for those with a longer index than the ring finger the risk dropped to 33 percent, while for men under 60 the risk decrease reached 87 percent.
The ratio of the lengths of the two fingers mentioned above - formed during the prenatal period - indicates, among other things, the different levels of sex hormones that the child is exposed to in the womb.
If you don't have testosterone, you have a longer index.
Previous research had shown that it is testosterone that helps the development of prostate cancer.
Professor Vacla Paces, a renowned Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, told CTK that he was aware of the study but did not seem to believe that the link between finger length and cancer was "fully demonstrated".
