The Democratic Routine
Support for democracy in Latin America continues to increase, as does support for private enterprise.
Crime has become a bigger concern than unemployment.
And Brazil is seen as more influential than the United States in much of the region.
These are some of the findings of the latest Latinobarómetro survey in 18 countries published exclusively by The Economist.
Since the survey has been carried out regularly since 1995, it follows the changes in attitudes in the region.
Two related findings emerge from the results of this year's survey, conducted in September and early October.
The first is the pretty sunny mood of Latin America.
The second is the increasing stability of attitudes towards democracy and its main institutions.
Support for democracy has increased significantly in several countries around the South American Pacific (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has averaged 6% a year since 2002, support for democracy has increased from a minimum of 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
It also increased in Mexico, where the economy recovered after suffering a sharp decline in production last year.
But only about half of respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous countries in the region, are convinced Democrats, which brings the regional average down (see Table 2).
Some 44% of respondents in the region said they were satisfied with the way democracy in their country was functioning in practice, the same figure as last year but with a sharp increase from 25% in 2001 (Graph 3)
Some 34% said they trusted their country's Parliament and 45% their government, the same as last year in both cases, but up sharply from 2003 (respectively 17% and 24%).
Ten years ago, economic problems in Latin America shaken support for democracy.
If this has been maintained during the global financial crisis, it is certainly because many American countries have experienced only a brief recession and have enjoyed a strong recovery.
In addition, a social security system has helped to protect the poor.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty only increased slightly in 2009 and has fallen again this year, to 32 percent.)
But mood varies greatly from country to country (see Chart 4).
Brazil's good economic performance and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, translates into a widely shared sense of progress
This is more rare in Mexico and Central America where the recession has been more severe and where violent crime has worsened.
For only the second time since the survey began, more respondents across Latin America as a whole cited crime as the most important problem for their country rather than unemployment (see Table 5).
Some 31% say they or a loved one has been the victim of a crime in the past year, but this figure is down from 38% last year and is the lowest since 1995.
Stronger economic performance is reflected in the increase in support for private enterprise and the market economy: about 71% of respondents in the region say private enterprise is essential for development, compared with 56% in 2007 (see Chart 6).
Some 58% believe that the market economy is the only system that will make their country developed, compared with 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela agree with this view (and 80% support private enterprise); even though their left-wing president, Hugo Chavez, expropriates many private enterprises.
Brazil is the largest leader in the region, with 19% of respondents mentioning it (compared to 18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, unchanged from last year) and Venezuela (9%, down 11% from last year).
But the United States is considered the most influential country by respondents in Mexico and most of Central America, while Venezuela enjoys this distinction in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
