Grammy Award nominations: Jazz singer Esperanza Spalding is a surprise selection in the "Best New Artist" category
Do it at the request of a president, and people are required to know about it.
Esperanza Spalding, the 26-year-old jazz bassist and singer handpicked by President Obama to perform at his 2009 Nobel Peace Prize ceremony, marked one of the surprise Grammy Awards this year with a major nomination in the "Best New Artist" category.
Considering that Spalding has been a well-known figure on the jazz scene since his 2008 album, "Esperanza", the nomination remains somewhat mysterious but is consistent with Grammy Awards rules that an artist must not release more than three albums before recording; which "establishes the artist's public identity".
Her ambitious 2010 album, "Chamber Music Society", certainly took a step forward and, given her slightly engaging vocal style, her skilful hand of pop and funk and Latin influences, it is possible to draw at least one dotted line in Spalding compared to the flashing success of Norah Jones in 2003, the closest equivalent for Grammy Award voters considering jazz productions in this category in recent years.
Elsewhere, Grammy voters rightly honored the Vijay Iyer Trio's "Historicity" in the "Instrumental Album" category, a thrilling departure from a recording that was one of the top favorites last year.
Among the competitors will be "Moody 4B" by veteran saxophonist James Moody and "Positootly" by keyboardist John Beasley.
Trombone Shorty, New Orleans's favorite loud voice and frequent guest on HBO's "Treme", was honored in the contemporary jazz category; which also leans strongly toward a certain fusion with albums by Stanley Clarke, John McLaughlin and Jeff Lorber.
Wild Darcy James Argue's Secret Society, familiar with steampunk, won some well-deserved recognition in the big band category; competing with the rich chamber-jazz of the Billy Childs Ensemble and eternal adventurer Dave Holland whose live octet album "Pathways" was a fine example of the bassist's democratic hand as bandleader.
Grammy Award nominations: Michael Daugherty and Steve Mackey lead in classical categories
The classic nominations for the 53rd annual Grammy Awards include a mix of landscapes from musicians and composers from around the world.
Among the nominations are Michael Daugherty's "Deus Ex Machina" for piano and orchestra, with five "yes"s; and Steve Mackey's "Dreamhouse", an electric orchestral work, with three "yes".
Among the nominees with connections to Southern California is Estonian composer Arvo Pärt for his Symphony No. 4, "Los Angeles", a work commissioned by the Los Angeles Philharmonic and which opened the Walt Disney Concert Hall in 2009.
The Madolin Concerto by Los Angeles-based composer Avner Dorman is also in contention for a prize.
The classical nominations are divided into 13 categories covering orchestral, opera, choral and solo recordings.
A category for the classical producer of the year features five nominees: Blanton Alspaugh, David Frost, Tim Handley, Marina and Victor Ledin and James Mallinson.
Nominations for the classical album include Bruckner's Symphonies No. 3 and 4 of the Royal Concertgebouw Orchestra; Daugherty's "Deus Ex Machina" and "Metropolis Symphony" of the Nashville Symphony Orchestra; Steven Mackey's "Dreamhouse" of the Boston Modern Orchestra Project and Synergy Vocals; "Sacrificium - the Art of the Castrati" featuring various artists; and Verdi's "Requiem" of the Chicago Symphony Orchestra and Chorus.
In the opera category, the nominees are Berg's "Lulu" by the Royal Opera House Orchestra, Adolf Hasse's "Marc Antonio e Cleopatra" by Ars Lyrica Houston; Kaija Saariaho's "Love Far Away" by the Deutsches Symphony-Orchester Berlin; Rodion Shchedrin's "The Enchanted Wanderer" by the Orchestra and Chorus of the Mariinsky Theatre; and Arthur Sullivan's "Ivanhoe" by the BBC National Orchestra of Wales.
Composers who are in place for the Grammy Awards for Contemporary Composition include Pärt for Symphony No. 4, Daugherty for "Deus Ex Machina", Hans Werner Henze for "Appassionatamente Plus", Magnus Lindberg for "Graffiti" and Shchedrin for "The Wanderer Enchanted".
Pärt's Symphony No. 4 premiered at Disney Hall in January 2009 in a performance recorded by the Los Angeles Philharmonic Orchestra, conducted by Esa-Pekka Salonen.
The 30-minute work is nicknamed "Los Angeles" and is dedicated to the former oil tycoon Mikhail Khodorkovsky, imprisoned in Russia.
Dorman's "Mandolin Concerto" was nominated for his solo instrumental performance with an orchestra.
The Los Angeles composer said he wrote the 15-minute piece specifically for mandolin performer Avi Avital, who played the concerto with the Metropolis Ensemble, based in New York City.
"I wrote it using sounds from the Middle East and a large number of North African ranges and rhythms", Dorman said in a telephone interview.
Orchestra conductor Pierre Boulez, 85, was nominated for the category of Best Orchestra Performance for conducting the Chicago Symphony Orchestra in a recording of Stravinsky's works.
Among the instrumental soloists who received nominations were the pianists Nelson Freire and Marc-André Hamelin; the organist Paul Jacobs; the violinist Julia Fischer; and the harpist Sarah Schuster Ericsson.
This year, there are only nominated soloists: Anne Sofie Von Otter, Cecilia Bartoli, Lucie Duchonová, Vivica Genaux and Measha Brueggergosman.
In the classical mixing category, soprano Jessye Norman received a nomination for her recording of "Racines: My Life, My Song"
