A microbe that tolerates arsenic raises the possibility of new life on Earth or elsewhere.
The discovery of a strange bacterium that can use arsenic as a nutrient, expands the field to find new life forms on Earth and perhaps beyond.
Although researchers have discovered the unusual bacteria here on Earth, they say it shows that life has possibilities beyond the major elements that were considered essential.
"This organism has a double capacity".
"It can develop with either phosphorus or arsenic".
"That's why it's very special, even if it's far from being a really 'strange' life form", said Paul Davies C.W. of Arizona State University, co-author of the report in the online edition of Thursday's Science.
Six major elements have long been considered essential for life: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus, and sulfur.
But researchers have found that the bacteria, discovered in Mono Lake, California, is able to continue to grow after replacing phosphorus with arsenic.
"We wonder what is still possible", said Ariel Anbar D. of Arizona State University, co-author of the report.
The discovery is important in the search for life beyond the Earth because researchers need to be able to recognize life, to know what life looks like, Anbar says.
The study focuses on a microbe found on Earth.
However, the announcement of a press conference to discuss the find, which did not disclose details of the find, has generated widespread speculation on the Internet that the report may reveal the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
That was not the case.
The discovery "shows that in other planetary environments organisms may be able to use other elements to act on biochemistry and that the 'standard' set of elements, which we consider absolutely necessary for life, may not be fixed", said Charles Cockell, professor at the Institute for Planetary and Space Scientific Research, Open University, Milton Keynes, United Kingdom.
Cockell wasn't on the research team.
"This work is new because it shows the substitution of one element for another in basic biochemistry and biochemical structure", Cockell added.
It wasn't a random discovery.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA's Institute of Astrology, who led the study, chose Mono Lake because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar, so she speculated that a microbe exposed to both substances might be able to replace each other.
"Arsenic is toxic mainly because its chemical behavior is very similar to that of phosphorus".
"As a result, organisms have difficulty distinguishing these elements separately".
"But arsenic is different enough that it does not work exactly like phosphorus; it penetrates the inside and, in a way, gums the work of our biochemical machine", Anbar explained.
The researchers collected the bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and exposed it to increasing concentrations of arsenic to which it was able to adapt and grow.
The microbe grows better with phosphorus, but the fact that it can live with arsenic instead raises the possibility that a form of life using arsenic can occur naturally, either elsewhere on Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said that the idea that arsenic could be replaced with phosphorus was not new; but nothing ever showed that it could work.
Arsenic was more common in the early days of Earth's existence, she says, and so researchers have speculated that early life forms may have used it.
This suggests that there might be other ways of forming life, not just the way life on Earth was formed in the beginning", said Foster, who was not part of the Wolfe-Simon research team.
The research was funded by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Institutes of Health.
