The lion is ready to red again, the restructuring of MGM is just waiting for the final green light from the courthouse
After 18 months of turmoil and uncertainty, MGM finally got the green light to start from scratch.
A federal bankruptcy judge in New York City officially praised Thursday the "prepackaged" plan by creditors that about $5 billion in debt would be wiped out, paving the way for the 86-year-old entertainment company to focus its efforts on producing and distributing films and television shows.
With Thursday's decision that the plan meets the requirements of the U.S. Bankruptcy Code, there are no legal barriers left to MGM getting back on the water under the tutelage of Entertainment Spyglass founders Gary Barber and Roger Birnbaum, who will become the CEOs of what will be a lightweight studio.
Staff will be reduced to about 320 out of 400 at the start.
MGM will not actually emerge from Chapter 11 until JPMorgan Chase has concluded a $500 million credit facility to finance MGM's new operations and production.
It is currently being distributed under licence by the investment bank, which is itself valued at $75 million, and is expected to be financed by mid-December.
The studio's restructuring process began in May 2009 when investment bank Moelis & Co. was hired to advise management on how to place its finances as it could not afford to pay interest amounting to $300 million per year.
In August, CEO Harry Sloan was replaced by Stephen Cooper, a former Enron CEO and restoration expert known for his work at Krispy Kreme Doughnuts.
Moelis and Cooper's attempts to solve MGM's financial difficulties and satisfy the studio's 140+ creditors took much longer than expected.
After months of discussions, the parties agreed, at the end of 2009, to sell the company.
However, the auction attracted few bidders, none of whom were willing to pay the additional $2 billion the creditors were looking for.
In the spring of this year, everything had to be rebuilt as the MGM team began work on a restructuring plan which, after months of disagreements and internal debates, was finally approved by creditors in late October.
When MGM officially emerged from bankruptcy in the following weeks, the companies Moelis and Cooper received multi-million dollar bonuses for their work.
Moelis & Co., which has already received $1.2 million, will receive a payment of $9.5 million.
Cooper's companies, which have raised $375,000 a month for their corporate management services, will receive a $4 million "success premium".
Barber and Birnbaum plan to relaunch production at MGM, which has only released one film this year, and to put together an annual list of seven or eight films that would be released starting in 2012.
They also intend to co-finance two films based on "The Hobbit", with Warner Bros.
The studio must make a separate loan of between $265 million and $275 million to finance its stake in these two films, which are to be directed by Peter Jackson.
Investor Carl Icahn, who owns about 18 percent of MGM's debt, tried to merge the studio with Lions Gate Entertainment, where he is the main shareholder.
However, recent discussions between the two companies have not led to an agreement.
