Bringing a softer side to maintaining order in China
Tang Shenbin was walking through a city square as a trained city sergeant, strictly inspecting his nerve loads, quietly issuing orders to a military authority.
He wanted the female members of Chengguan - imposing public policy officials in China, feared and despised for their arbitrary repression and inclination to violence - to give a certain impression to a group of viewers.
"Stand up straight!"
"Be careful!"
"Show them what pretty girls look like", he said.
Four girls, who had barely spent their teenage years in white gloves, wearing identical olive-colored jackets and trousers, were on guard duty.
Four pairs of black heels, aligned with the rule.
Four well-groomed hats perched on top of hair tied by a blue and white striped knot.
"Personally, I think they look average", said Mr. Tang, disdainfully.
"The models are beautiful".
More than one government has tried to refresh the image of China's urban inspectors.
One city required all new recruits to have a high school diploma.
Guangdong province has traded the grey-green uniforms for a blue one that is said to be more engaging.
Wuhan, central China, replaced the down-eye with a strong: in 2009, a report reported that 50 officers surrounded an uncontrollable snack cart by staring at it, firmly for half an hour, until the colporteur packed his bags and left.
Xindu, an urban district of 680,000 in Chengdu, chose to do a large image operation.
Since 2003, the district has completed its urban street police force with 13 women, specially selected for their appearance, complexion and young age.
The idea is to give the police a softer, more feminine side.
Unfortunately, even Scarlett Johansson might have trouble getting attention on this underground city brigade in China.
And for good reason, critics will say.
Unlike the police, these officers are only authorized to enforce municipal orders by imposing fines or other administrative sanctions.
But the Chinese media portray the news from a different reality.
In January 2008, inspectors in Hubei province beat to death an observer after he used his cell phone to film them dispersing a protest against a landfill.
Last year, a training manual for Beijing inspectors, stolen and posted online, describes how to effectively defeat criminals without shedding blood.
This year in Shanghai, a pastry colporteur was left with a brain injury after a fight with five officers.
A violent video game, available for download online, shows Chinese trained inspectors raiding street vendors.
"Chengguan has marked the government", lamented China Daily, a national publication, last year, after another controversy over tactics.
The paper called for a "true, complete cleanup".
Skeptics say the approach is far from it.
After the district announced in October that eight new female recruits were to be hired, an editorial in The Beijing Evening News questioned whether women had real jobs or whether they were just tourist entertainment.
The answer seems to be a little bit of both.
The district's announcement required female candidates, aged 18 to 22, to have a beautiful figure and "five facial features in the right order".
They must be taller than average, or 1.6 meters or 5 feet, 2.5 inches.
Retirement at 26 is compulsory.
Officials said the work was too physically demanding for women over 25.
"It's their image that matters", a district official told Rednet.com, a quasi-governmental website.
"First, the outer qualities of the candidates will determine whether they are suitable - they are the height, weight, facial features, etc".
Then comes temperament and "inner qualities".
Chengguan women are like flower pots, he said, adding: "In addition to being pots, they will have other responsibilities.
Zheng Lihua, deputy director of the city district management office, does not agree with this description.
But he noted that height requirements were the standard in many Chinese job offers for both sexes.
This is the case with the requirement for the order of facial features.
What it means beautiful is a subject of debate among the Chinese.
Of course, disabled or disfigured persons do not have to apply.
"We cannot let a crippled or lame person come here to serve", says Mr. Zheng.
"It wouldn't give a good image".
Liu Yi, who patrols Baoguang Square near a monastery, is 22 years old and has a slightly curved mouth.
She doesn't consider showing off her appearance to be sexist, she said.
"Do you think I look sexy in this uniform?" she asked in a disappointed look.
Xu Yang, his 21-year-old colleague at the trenches, says, "Our job is to present the image of the city".
They did not object to their mandate being limited, they said, because they had higher career ambitions than simply chasing salesmen out of the alleys where they were supposed to limit their activities.
Every morning, the team deals with a dozen street vendors who move quickly on foot or by bicycle, trying to sell as many tofu and breadcrumbs as possible before they run away.
"Master Wang, you must leave".
"We've told you many times already!" said Ms. Xu as a salesman ran away on foot, temporarily abandoning his noodle cart.
The agents describe their duties as more monotonous than arduous.
"It's pretty much the same thing every day", said 20-year-old Huang Jing, who studies after-work marketing.
"It's a big routine".
One reason is that female agents do not have the power of their male counterparts to confiscate the sellers' property.
They can only threaten to report offenders to their male superiors.
This tends to protect them from the sudden public exposures of hostility against the bureaucracy that are common throughout China.
This year, hundreds of citizens in Kunming, the capital of Yunnan province, revolted after false rumors spread that Chengguan agents had killed a salesman.
In one night, more than a dozen Chengguan police and officers were injured, 14 government vehicles were overturned or set on fire.
Xindu has so far escaped such violence.
But peace is hardly guaranteed.
Just two blocks from the Baoguang Square, where female officers were patrolling that morning, more than 50 people gathered on the street corner.
Officers confiscated a motorcycle that was being repaired on the sidewalk rather than in a store, as required by regulations.
The motorcycle owner was shouting at the scandal.
