Can civility bring the divisions closer?
After a campaign marked by inventiveness and negativity, a minimum of civility broke out in Washington this week.
Is this a sign of a real bipartisan cooperation going forward or an illusory moment before the rapid return to partisan struggle in the capital?
The meeting between President Obama and congressional leaders on Tuesday produced no breakthroughs on the major issues that must be addressed during the "walking duck" session.
But obviously there was at least a polite discussion about the differences between the two parties and the recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than another episode where each side wanted to score points.
The public meeting of the Committee on the President's Deficit on Wednesday was equally civilized, despite the political differences that remain between the members.
It seems clear that the close interaction of several months has created mutual respect that transcends ideological divisions, but which still divides members.
It is hardly enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
The two sides are now in a period of mutual testing and testing to obtain signs of cooperation and compromise, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and the patience of voters for renewed partisan war.
That is why Tuesday's meeting and subsequent comments from participants revealed a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too big and too deep to suggest a rapid change in the climate that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it's taxation, spending, health care, or rights, both sides are miles away.
But the November election had moderated Washington, at least in the short term.
"There is no doubt that things have changed in tone", said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official now at the Ethics and Public Policy Center.
"It's inevitable after the election.
Elections arouse party passions and then they fade.
It's good".
On some issues, including those on the agenda of the "walking duck" session, the Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush's tax cuts are due to expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favor of that.
Both parties want to find a way to preserve some or all of it, permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, a compromise on extending unemployment benefits is possible, even if it is because Republicans cannot afford to give the impression that they are in favour of tax cuts for the rich while denying unemployment benefits to unemployed workers.
After Tuesday's meeting at the White House, there is more optimism about possible agreement on the issues raised during the session on the "walking duck" with the ratification of the New START pact.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that fruitful cooperation on the most pressing issues of the "lame duck" session will not necessarily lead to a better understanding between the two parties when the 112th Congress meets in January.
Instead, he says, a period of disagreement is likely, if not inevitable.
"Once the things that need to be done are done, psychology in the short term will return to one of the confrontations", he said.
Wehner also expressed his widely shared skepticism that civility would lead to genuine cooperation.
"I consider most of what happens between now and 2012 as a pre-show or a shadow-boxing compared to the main event of 2012", he said.
The reasons for this are closely linked to the composition of the new Republican majority in the House and the tea-loving voters who helped to create it.
But Republican leaders are aware of the dangers if they go too far, they know they must try to live up to their promises to cut public spending and repeal the new health care law.
These pro-democracy positions are already clear in the first reactions to the Committee's recommendations, which include reforming the tax code and raising certain taxes, pushing back the retirement age and reducing expenditure.
Co-chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have chosen one of the most difficult tasks in Washington and, they say, have imposed the deficit issue on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the 18-member committee to issue their plan as an official recommendation, and they have had a hard time getting to that number.
The greatest resistance remains among the group's elected officials, suggesting that there are few reasons or will to compromise on tax matters, at least today.
Galston has two phases in the fight between the White House and the Republicans in Congress.
The first will come next year in the form of partisan confrontations, as Republicans challenge Obama on budget, taxes and health care; followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What would be the cause of the change?
The public opinion.
It is widely proven that despite the party spirit of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties work together.
If the confrontation leads to a deadlock, as in 1995, then both parties will watch the public's reaction closely.
Whoever is judged to be a loser will have to change course and find compromises.
But that would still be an optimistic view.
The partisan spirit and polarization are greater today than they were in the mid-1990s and there seems to be a greater ideological gap between Obama and the Republicans in Congress than there was then between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as a mere prelude to a more significant election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civility presented this week could be appreciated by many Americans.
But it will take much more effort on the part of both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
