Zapatero and the German Red Line
Berlin has chosen to remain in the euro, but it has set the conditions for the whole Union.
The tensions in the markets have led to a double government response.
On the one hand, José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero announced new adjustment methods, which range from tax reductions for SMEs, regulation of private investment agencies or the removal of the EUR 426 unemployment benefit without professional contribution to the privatisation of 49% of AENA, the management of Barajas and El Prat airports and 30% of the State Lotteries.
On the other hand, Vice-President Elena Salgado, with the support of former President Felipe González, joins criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel over her responsibility to unleash the current crisis.
How should we interpret these movements?
It is worth mentioning that Merkel's position is not a mistake in her communication policy.
On the contrary, it is another constraint on the difficult process of redefining the euro.
And here Germany has a radically new vision of what its future should be, which clashes with that of maintaining the old traditions of most of its partners.
In Germany, the three possible outcomes of the crisis are being speculated in the face of European resistance.
The first, a strong euro, integrated by itself, Austria and Holland, among other countries, and the south would leave the monetary zone.
The second is the recovery of the Mark, even though it now seems like science fiction, with a very favorable stream of opinion, almost 50% of the population.
The third is a new design of the euro, in line with the German proposals for greater macroeconomic control, fiscal rigour, fines for countries that break them, possible suspensions of payments of one of them and the extension to the private sector of the costs of potential adjustments.
The German position is clear and has been defined for a long time, so now there is no room for excuses.
First, in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission were boosting deficits, the German Government devised a constitutional reform to prevent them from 2016.
This was the first sign of divergence between what Germany thought it should do (tax rigour and fiscal stability) and what its European partners, including France, were doing.
The second blow from the Central European country was when Merkel barely extended the decision to save Greece.
It has since been the subject of fierce criticism, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and public opinion and the press were against rescuing Greece.
Finally, towards the end of October, Merkel once again expressed a clear position, calling for the reform of the EU treaties to enable a country's bailout and at the same time forcing private lenders to bear a share of the cost.
This position has been interpreted as anti-European, as it has precipitated the Irish crisis and the rest.
But his proposal, although somewhat sweetened, was approved and in the months to come we should be witnessing the Union reform process that makes these measures possible from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not think it will cross.
And it tells us all that even if we now have to take measures that we may not agree with too much, from that date on the old functioning of the euro would be over.
2013 will mark the birth of a new monetary zone, where countries that break the rules will be severely sanctioned, they may be forced to declare themselves to be out of payments and, in this case, the private sector will also bear a share of the costs.
Germany is pointing out that we must follow a strong growth path with high savings and investment rates, moderation in consumption, improvements in productivity and competitiveness and positive external balances.
An alternative based on debt and construction, with huge gaps in the balance of payments, such as the one that led Spain's growth in the boom years, will simply not be tolerated.
The bet is clear.
And it would be a shame not to hear it.
It is not just a question of bringing the public deficit back to 3% in 2013.
What we're asked to do is much harder.
And what he absolutely shouldn't do in these circumstances is fool ourselves.
