Sport and fraud
Tricks similar to Alonso and Ramos's against Ajax show ingenuity but not the will to escape punishment.
The expulsion of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) during the November 23 Champions League match against Ajax has caused much ink to be poured on the anti-sport nature of such behaviour and whether both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As we know, minutes before the game was over (their team was already clearly winning), both players deliberately wasted time when they made mistakes to determine the referee to show them the second yellow card.
Thus, as Real Madrid will eventually lead their group, both players will be subject to the regulatory sanction during the next game of the draw against Auxerre and will be able to go without cards to the next stage.
Eventually, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee sanctioned the team's coach, José Mourinho, with two games and various financial amounts to the players involved.
The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new practice, if not rather common in the football world.
It's so widespread that it's part of the ethos, the unwritten rules, but followed, of this sport.
Part of the debate in the case is due to the fact that this has been played by a team from the Real Madrid entity (who in their anthem showcases nobility and honour and who on past occasions has fined their players for similar acts) and the orchestrated dramatisation, it seems, by Mourinho, which adds one more episode to his long history as a histrionic and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate is whether this type of behaviour, which is not expressly prohibited by the regulations, is contrary to the principles of sport, that is, whether such actions are fraudulent; they are indeed actions which respect the rules of sport but seem to elude their meaning.
The question is to examine the kind of damage they cause to the spirit of sports.
One of the assets that includes sportsmanship is the physical integrity of the opposing players, an aspect that has not been compromised by these actions, that is, there has been no violent gambling.
Another of these goods that is alluded to with proper play is to prevent the team of offending players from unfairly taking advantage of the opposing team, which is not the case either.
However, the paradoxical fact of the action of the Real Madrid players is that it does not accommodate what is normally characterized as cheating or fraud of the law, as its violation of the rules was not done in secret to try to avoid sanction, but their action precisely tried to be as obvious as possible to receive the penalty from the referee.
They waited and willingly accepted the punishment.
Another question is what kind of advantage the offenders gain from the deliberate errors examined.
It seems necessary to note that neither the opponent is put at a disadvantage nor the player gains an advantage in the same match, because the result of the action is obviously to leave their own team with fewer players.
And that's not a useful strategy for the next game either, because the club couldn't count on those players.
Obviously the advantage is that players will start the next Champions League phase without any cards that could threaten their participation in a future match.
But this is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of uncertainty, because the team could be eliminated suddenly and besides that, with this action players perform a penalty match and move on to the second round of cards, in which the suspension due to the buildup of cards occurs with one less than in the first round.
So, climbing the ladder is not so clear that it's an advantage.
Finally, these actions are not contrary to the spirit of sport, which still includes the making of strategic decisions that promote maximum profit from what the rules allow.
In our case, the gamblers did not act to avoid the penalty (this would be a clear case of fraud by law), but instead they chose the moment when they submitted to it.
They made a strategic decision without escaping the penalty or escaping it.
Even though the line between genius and law fraud is widespread, I think we've had a clear case of genius here.
The controversy, I think, arises because of two factors: because there were two self-deportations and because of how to pass on the director to provoke them.
The damage to the principles of sport caused by these actions is not as ethical as it is aesthetic.
