Luisa Valenzuela read a text dedicated to Gonzalo Celorio that Shultz later defined as a great story, with Luisa in the first person as the protagonist who seeks to find out what the "plague" is, she goes from one doctor to another, without getting an answer, only clues in the same narrative thread.
She came out of the infectious disease clinic convinced: "Patience is not my strength, it may be my wound".
Finally, after a frustrated approach to the trauma doctor who cut his breath in the middle of the hallway, but who explained that wound is not a scientific term; the psychoanalyst revealed the mystery: "the wound is what is actually open, the symbolic is the scar".
The protagonist sighed with relief and concluded: "On the wound I could only know that it is the one that is actually open and that it does not exist", but convinced that the pleasures and traps of language must be closely linked.
Valenzuela, the writer, played with both of them.
Nicaraguan Sergio Ramírez also told a fascinating story called "Elohe de la invención", where the finger on the wound is not named but at some point is discovered.
With touches of magical realism, he talks about a famous sorceress who touched clouds, turned people back who had gone far or repaired virtues that a lady had lost, a narrative that then turns to talk about America, the great news that had its own chroniclers from the beginning and quotes Bernal Díaz del Castillo who criticizes the excesses of the narrations of the conquering captains.
"The inventor of all of us (the writers) mocked false witnesses who appeared in stories presented as real, but in a way we would never have told the history of America with an imagination that lacked even modesty".
Nevertheless, he stressed, "fools and liars have the best imagination" and here reality converges with lies, it is no longer known what part of the narrative belongs to one band or another, where fiction literature reaches its peak.
This is actually called the 'Cervantes tradition'.
"It is through his legacy that we are what we are".
In turn, the writer Mayra Montyero noted and applauded the variety of interpretations brought about by the invitation of the FIL with her round table The debt on the wound.
