"I think that good literature, good poetry, good songs contain a tacit commitment that is not of course premeditated", she said, after citing that the reality of literature is the communication and dimension of the commitment that is established between the author and the readers, and that it is a 'chemical reaction' of the latter.
The evening ended with the intervention of the Spanish poet Luis García Montero who also stressed "it is due to the wound of the committed writer".
He considered that in a world that is also rapidly changing in intellectual habits and conscience control, and that dogmatism is in its favor, "behind every affirmation is a little no and behind every denial a little yes".
"To be masters of our own feelings and masters of reality, we must nuance: and nuance often means putting our finger on the wound and disturbing people who feel very comfortable thinking in caricature, in black and white, in established ideas and without nuance and disturbing also the powers that prefer a world in black and white", he said, urging to recover the sense of writing.
