The European Union changes the rules for obtaining visas
People must go to the Visa Applicants Service before their interview in the Consular Section; the waiting time will be reduced.
From 10 January 2011, the visa processing procedure at the U.S. Embassies and Consulates will change.
With the new procedure, most applicants will have to report to the Visa Applicants Service Centres (ASC) before their interview in the Consular Section.
The ASC staff will take the applicant's biometric information, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section before the interview.
The new procedure will provide certain benefits for applicants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, there will be no need to pay for an appointment, another payment for processing the visa and another for the postal service to deliver the document.
The applicant will make a one-time payment covering all three services.
The current rate will remain the same: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visa applications (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for business and investor visas.
Persons wishing to renew their visa will not be required to appear for an interview with the Consular Representative, they will only appear at the nearest ASC where they will present their documents and their fingerprints will be taken.
Because biometric information will be taken at the ASC, applicants who wish to have a second interview in the Consular Section will stay there less than before.
Similarly, visa applicants at the Consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer have to pay the extra service fee of $26 USD.
For more information on the new visa application procedure, please visit the following page: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/bulletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
