A global plan to refurbish lighting
The UN proposed a plan in Cancun to renovate domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries to achieve a reduction in greenhouse gases (GHGs) that is almost one third of the additional reduction needed to stabilize the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan follows the major concrete projects the UN hopes to have adopted in Cancun to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments by the industrialized countries.
According to the plan submitted yesterday, if the incandescent bulbs that still hold 50 to 70% of the market were replaced by fluorescent light bulbs or, better, by light-emitting diode (DEL or "LED") bulbs, the majority of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of GHG emitted on the planet to light humans would be avoided.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
That's equivalent to 70 percent of the emissions from the global fleet.
In Copenhagen last year, major emitter countries such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans that are expected to increase global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But it will take another 5 Gt to stabilize the climatic rise to 2 degrees Celsius by 2020 to prevent it from getting out of control.
In incandescent bulbs, 95 percent of the energy is dissipated as heat and the remaining 5 percent is produced by light.
With fluoro-compact bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by 75% and with new LED bulbs, this energy requirement is reduced by a further twofold.
Fluocompetent bulbs last an average of 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, like those launched by the manufacturer Philips this week - which was also a part of the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent light bulb, giving an idea of the possible economy with a replacement plan that would apply to 100 countries.
These new bulbs can also work with rheostats and emit very little heat.
And they don't contain any mercury.
Several experts have expressed reservations about fluorescent lamps because they contain mercury and must be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries unless manufacturers put in place directives.
But the report says that the world's main source of mercury emissions is not the fluorescent bulb but rather coal-fired power plants, which emit a lot of mercury to produce the waste electricity in incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury per year.
The report details the gains each country would make from this international programme.
For example, Indonesia would save a billion dollars a year in electricity purchases and eight million tons of CO2, the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants that would cost it 2.5 billion dollars to build.
