Hackers Avengers and Diligent Spy
The WikiLeaks case has a double value.
On the one hand, it is a clear scandal, a scandal which is only seen as a scandal in the face of the hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it heralds profound changes at the international level, and foreshadows a future dominated by regression.
But let's go in order.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation that every file made up by a secret service (of any nation) is composed exclusively of press clippings.
The "extraordinary" US revelations about Berlusconi's sexual habits only report what for months could be read in any newspaper (except those Berlusconi owns), and the sinister caricatured profile of Gaddafi has long been a subject of sketch cabaret artists.
The rule that secret files should only be composed of new information already known is essential to the dynamics of the secret services, and not only in this century.
If you go to a bookstore devoted to esoteric literature, you will find that each book repeats (on the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rose-Croix) exactly what was already written in earlier books.
And not only because the author of occult texts does not like to do new research (or does not know where to look for news on the non-existent), but because those who practice occultism believe only in what they already know, and it confirms what they have already learned.
That's the mechanism of Dan Brown's success.
I'll go to the secret files.
The informant is lazy, and the head of the secret service (otherwise he could be, I know, a Freedmen's editor) is lazy (or of a limited mind), and he only keeps what he admits to be true.
The top-secret information about Berlusconi that the U.S. Embassy in Rome was sending to the State Department was the same as the one that Newsweek had published the week before.
So why were the revelations on these files so loud?
On the one hand, they say what every educated person knows already, that embassies, at least since the end of World War II, and since heads of state can call or fly to dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, except for a few small representative exercises, have become spy centres.
Any investigative film viewer knows this very well, and it is only through hypocrisy that we pretend to ignore it.
However, publicly repeating it violates the duty of hypocrisy and serves to cast a bad light on American diplomacy.
Second, the idea that any hacker could capture the most secret secrets of the world's most powerful country is a major blow to the State Department's prestige.
The scandal therefore does not put victims in crisis as much as the "borrowers".
But let's get to the bottom of what happened.
Back in Orwell's day, we could imagine all power as a Big Brother controlling every move of his subjects.
The Orwellian prophecy had come true in full since, being able to control every movement through the telephone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the highway borrowed and so on, the citizen became the complete victim of the eye of the power.
But when we show, as it happens now, that even the crypts of power secrets cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control report ceases to be one-way and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - elected as the citizen's avenger - can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that no longer has the ability to keep its own secrets hold?
It is true, as Georg Simmel has said before, that a real secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that knowing everything about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is indeed an empty secret, because it is in the public domain; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks did, that Hillary Clinton's secrets were empty secrets means to take away all her power.
WikiLeaks did no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but it did too much to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this injury inflicted on a very powerful power?
It is clear that in the future, states will no longer be able to put any reserved information online - it would be like posting it on a street corner poster.
But it is just as obvious that with modern technology, there is no hope of keeping confidential communications on the phone.
Nothing is easier than finding out if and when a head of state flew around and contacted one of his colleagues.
How will private and reserved relations be maintained in the future ?
I know that my prediction is science fiction at the moment and is therefore romantic, but I am forced to imagine government agents who travel discreetly in diligences on uncontrollable routes, carrying only memorized messages or, at best, hiding the rare information written in the heel of a shoe.
The information will be stored in single copies in locked drawers: basically, the Watergate espionage attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that technology is now advancing crabbily, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet has restored the wireless telegraph.
The analogue videotapes allowed film researchers to explore a film step by step, going back and forth and uncovering all the secrets of editing, whereas the digital CDs now only allow for chapter-by-chapter leaps, i.e. by macroportions.
High-speed trains take three hours from Rome to Milan, while air travel takes three and a half hours.
It is not surprising, then, that the politics and communication techniques are the same as those of horse-drawn carriages.
One last thought.
In the past, the press tried to understand what was going on in the secret embassies.
Now it's the embassies that ask the press for confidential information.
Climate: how France is distorting its funding pledges
One year after the Copenhagen Accord, it is time to examine the implementation of the promises of rapidly unblocked financing (so-called fast start or early financing) made by developed countries.
And the big French puzzles are revealed.
In the Copenhagen Accord, developed countries committed to providing $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has pledged EUR 7.2 billion over three years and France EUR 1.26 billion (or 420 million a year).
At the opening of COP16, the EU played a big game to convince its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast start funding: a report detailing the action of its Member States, a press conference, a big side event, the distribution of brochures...
Transparency is appreciated and appreciated for its fair value: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same with the same level of accuracy.
The EU announced that it had committed €2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on track to meet its commitment of €7.2 billion in 2012.
But when you look at the details, things are more complicated.
The Copenhagen agreement requires that this money be 'new and additional' to ensure that additional efforts are made without prejudice to public development aid.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission had proposed a harmonisation, some Member States, including France, blocked the procedure.
Today, each person chooses the reference that suits him best.
The European Commission, for example, has considered 2009 as a reference year: international funding is maintained, and it adds 150 million over three years under fast start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references in terms of year or level of public development aid.
On the contrary, France considers that the financing of 'all new projects' in 2010 is 'new and additional'.
In other words, there is no reference to previous years' expenditure or to the overall level of State aid for development.
In particular, the total amount of France's support to developing countries may remain stable (or even decrease) and it claims to respect its commitment to 'new and additional' financing.
Another crucial element is the distribution of gifts and loans.
Again, there is no rule and everyone chooses their own way of calculating.
Some, like France, consider that a euro borrowed is equal to a given euro.
Of course, this is hardly justifiable: the effort is incomparable.
If the use of loans can be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often projects related to emission mitigation that rely on more efficient technologies), it is wrong to present a euro to be recovered as equivalent to a euro given... At most, only the cost of the loan to the lending country (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate) should be counted against its commitments.
But France has only to reason with this: it is "respecting" its commitment of €420 million by making 91.5% loans (€389.8 million) and 8.5% donations (€36.1 million) - see the EU document to see for yourself.
It is the only EU country to use the loan so heavily.
Germany requires 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (other countries) fulfil their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union puts in 1 euro to meet its commitment, France puts in only 10 cents and considers the effort comparable.
That's a nice passing game.
In summary, in its fast start financing, France is conducting a double fraud: on the one hand, on the evolution of the action over time and on the other, on the reality of the financial effort.
With only €36.1 million, it can make it appear that it is spending €420 million on 'new and additional' projects in line with its promises.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that Bercy has arbitrated) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would other Member States continue to lend if they only lend?) and in the negotiations since developing countries are not completely fooled...
The chapter on early financing is only a small, relatively short-term matter compared with all the climate discussions.
But there could be a grain of sand in the huge machine that is the UNFCCC.
Let's hope that's not the case.
In any event, it is essential to learn from this first year of early financing.
First, France could announce a change in its accounting for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and fairness with the other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France could advance discussions on the issues of long-term financing (another crucial chapter currently discussed): the question of 'additionality' or the way loans are accounted for will not be avoided.
France could change its position to become as progressive on these issues as it is on others.
The hope is therefore in the new Minister for the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement on France's fast start and its vision of "additionality" and the use of loans would increase the level of international confidence needed to move forward in the discussions.
Warning against pesticides ingested by children
A 10-year-old child ingests 81 different chemicals in a day, according to a study published Wednesday by the Future Generations (formerly the Movement for the Rights and Respect of Future Generations).
The association, which warns that its results "have no statistical significance in view of the small number of samples analysed but are illustrative of the problem", purchased between July and September the food normally consumed in four meals and one snack in a day by a ten-year-old child in supermarkets in the Oise and Paris.
These types of meals, including official recommendations - five fresh fruits and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 liters of water a day - as well as sweets, have been examined by laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The balance sheet is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, 42 of which are classified as possible or probable carcinogens and five classified as certain carcinogens and 37 substances that may act as endocrine disruptors (EDs), according to studies by several institutions such as the International Cancer Research Centre.
"Although in almost all cases the legal limits for each individual chemical are not exceeded, our survey shows that the reality of consumer exposure to potentially carcinogenic and/or PE contaminants is of concern", notes the association.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible carcinogenic residues and three proven carcinogens and nearly 20 residues likely to disrupt the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, which the study envisaged as a container, contains traces of six chemicals, including a fungicide that is banned in France.
The same is true for the Kenyan green beans, included in lunch, which the study found traces of a potent insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, the cut steak, canned tuna, and even the breadstick and chewing gum were infused with pesticides and other chemicals.
The tap water was tested for nitrates and chloroform.
For dinner, salmon steak was the richest with 34 chemical residues detected and even examining the plastic plate used to heat the meal in the microwave was not exempt.
The final risk to the consumer of these "contaminant cocktails" "is probably underestimated", according to the study.
The European Ecology-Green Alliance (EE-LV) proposed "in the face of the urgency of the situation" to establish a moratorium on the use of pesticides in order to stop "the rise of diseases of civilization".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) reported the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
